{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491488"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:48:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"956"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/956"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.07,0.01,0.27,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110546"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/956"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92803"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2961"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12161"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department after a fall. She was found on the floor by her neighbour, who was unsure how long she had been lying there for but she had last been seen well 2 days ago. The neighbour has the patient\u0027s medication list, which reads perindopril, atorvastatin, oxybutynin, esomeprazole and amitriptyline. The patient is now alert but disoriented to time and place and is unsure why she is in hospital. She is complaining of pain in her left leg. Apart from a large bruise on the lateral aspect of her left thigh, the physical examination is unremarkable and her vital signs are within normal limits. She scores poorly on a mini-mental state examination. An X-ray of the left thigh is normal. Her serum creatinine is significantly elevated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations should be ordered to confirm the most likely cause of her acute kidney injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Creatine kinase","Lactate dehydrogenase","Haemoglobin","Urinary myoglobin","CT KUB"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this woman is rhabdomyolysis secondary to a long lie, resulting in an acute kidney injury (AKI). She may have been lying on the floor for a significant amount of time, resulting in muscle breakdown and the release of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecreatine kinase\u003C/strong\u003E (CK) is diagnostic of rhabdomyolysis.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E is a direct nephrotoxin and can result in acute tubular necrosis, it can be measured in the urine. It will be elevated in rhabdomyolysis induced AKI, however, it lacks the sensitivity of CK measurement as myoglobin may be absent in 25-50% of cases. Following injury, plasma myoglobin increases rapidly and is cleared within 24 hours, while serum CK levels rise 2\u201312 hours after muscle injury, peak at 3\u20135 days after injury, and decline over the subsequent 6\u201310 days. Therefore, CK provides a more reliable measure of rhabdomyolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT KUB\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful if suspecting an obstructive, or post-renal cause of acute kidney injury. However, given the history, this is less likely than an AKI related to rhabdomyolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere anaemia\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be a cause of a pre-renal AKI and therefore it would be worthwhile checking this patients \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E, however there is nothing in the stem that indicates the suspicion of severe anaemia and her AKI is more likely due to her long lie. In this case the bruise is unlikely to be extensive enough to have caused major blood loss to result in kidney hypoperfusion in the setting of normal heart rate and blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElevated \u003Cstrong\u003Elactate dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E may be seen in AKI, but similarly\u00a0would not specify the underlying aetiology.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rhabdomyolysis is a cause of acute kidney injury which is best diagnosed with creatine kinase"],"references":["Rahman M, Shad F, Smith MC. Acute kidney injury: a guide to diagnosis and management.. Am Fam Physician. 2012; 86 (7): p.631-9.","Nance JR, Mammen AL. Diagnostic evaluation of rhabdomyolysis. Muscle Nerve. 2015;51(6):793-810."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92803"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"956"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92803"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T09:19:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T09:19:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"956"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110546"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCou